text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Asian American discrimination in South Park%0a:Author: NickG%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 20:24%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-021730-40520#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 19:17-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-021730-40520#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aSouth Park often discriminates against a number of groups, and their representation of Asian-Americans is very stereotypical and offensive.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe following clip is one of many examples of the show South Park portraying Asian-Americans in a stereotypical way, in part by exaggerating stereotypes associated with how Asian-American immigrants speak.%0ahttps://youtu.be/xWf8JcRsq9k%0a%0aThis clip is making fun of the pronunciation of [l] in English words as [r] and portraying it as ungrammatical. In the clip, the Asian-Americans are depicted pronouncing "rely" as [ɹɪˈraɪ] instead of the SAE pronunciation [ɹɪˈlaɪ], "intellect" as [ˈɪntərekt] instead of [ˈɪntəlekt], and "look" as [rʊk] instead of [lʊk]. The exaggeration of this linguistic pattern alongside other stereotypical portrayals of the characters gives the impression that this accent is somehow inferior to SAE or ungrammatical in some way. %0aThis accent is common among many East Asian immigrants in America, in part because most East Asian languages do not have a phonological distinction between the [l] and [r] sound. In this clip specifically, South Park is making fun of a Chinese-American accent, but they have portrayed many Asian-Americans in a similar way.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
